      <hedline>
        <hl1>Europe's Mideast Role</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jonathan Portes letter on William Safire's Apr 23 article scoring British Foreign Sec Robin Cook's stand on Israeli-Palestinian peace talks (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire criticizes the British Foreign Secretary, Robin Cook, for ''all but endorsing Palestinian claims to a hill inside Jerusalem'' (column, April 23) and implies that Prime Minister Tony Blair and British Jewish leaders take a different view. But successive British governments, like the rest of the European Union, have recognized that Israel's annexation of East Jerusalem, and its West Bank settlements, is illegal under international law and a threat to peace.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire criticizes the British Foreign Secretary, Robin Cook, for ''all but endorsing Palestinian claims to a hill inside Jerusalem'' (column, April 23) and implies that Prime Minister Tony Blair and British Jewish leaders take a different view. But successive British governments, like the rest of the European Union, have recognized that Israel's annexation of East Jerusalem, and its West Bank settlements, is illegal under international law and a threat to peace.</p>
        <p>Mr. Safire is correct that the E.U. is the most important market for Israelis and Palestinians. That is why it is necessary for it to assist both parties in negotiating a just settlement. The E.U. should also use economic leverage to pressure Israel to fulfill its obligations under the Oslo agreements. In this, Mr. Blair would have the support of the vast majority of Labor Party members and of British Jews.</p>
        <p>JONATHAN PORTES</p>
        <p>New York, April 23, 1998</p>
      </block>
